  "text": "Migration squashing in Django spans 8 key files: (1) **squashmigrations.py** is the management command that generates squashed migrations - it collects migrations to squash, gathers operations, invokes the optimizer, sets `replaces`, and writes via MigrationWriter. (2) **migration.py** defines the `replaces` attribute on the Migration class for replaced-migrations tracking. (3) **loader.py** has `build_graph()` which processes `migration.replaces` to detect squashed migrations, handles cyclical squash replacement, and decides whether to call `remove_replaced_nodes` or `remove_replacement_node` on the graph; it also checks completeness of squashed migrations at lines 357-377. (4) **graph.py** provides `remove_replaced_nodes()`, `remove_replacement_node()`, and `validate_consistency()` for dependency graph validation after squashing. (5) **executor.py** has `detect_soft_applied()` which checks the applied state of squashed migrations vs. their replaced set. (6) **writer.py** serializes the `replaces` list into the squashed migration file. (7) **optimizer.py** optimizes the combined operations list during squash generation. (8) **autodetector.py** has a helper to parse squashed migration names (line 2058-2062).",
